t\'s doing while sentiment normalizes.\n\nThis is a bet on the most profitable consumer franchise in the world being temporarily cheap because people are scared. I\'ll take that bet.', 'conservative_history': '', 'neutral_history': '', 'latest_speaker': 'Judge', 'current_aggressive_response': 'Aggressive Analyst: I\'m looking at this analysis and frankly, I\'m struck by how much opportunity cost is being left on the table by the conservative framing. Let me work through this piece by piece.\n\nFirst, the governance risk point. Yes, the VP investigation is real, but here\'s where I think the analysis misses the mark. The investigation is of a single executive, not systemic regulatory action against the company itself. In China\'s current environment, when the Party wants to send a message to an industry, they act decisively and broadly—look at what happened to tech or education sectors in prior years. Moutai has faced "anti-corruption" pressures for over a decade and has only strengthened its position. The 91.5% gross margin isn\'t an accident; it\'s structural moat that regulatory discomfort hasn\'t dismantled in ten years of trying. The risk is priced in, but the resilience isn\'t.\n\nOn exports being "tiny"—this is exactly the kind of linear thinking that misses inflection points. Fourfold growth in Southeast Asia isn\'t about current size, it\'s about trajectory and validation. Moutai is proving it can travel culturally, which was the core bear case for years. The company is literally creating a new revenue engine while the market focuses on the old one\'s RPMs. By the time exports hit that 15-20% threshold the conservative analyst demands as "meaningful," the multiple expansion opportunity will be gone. You buy growth stories at the 4x inflection, not after they\'ve matured.\n\nThe structural consumption weakness argument frustrates me because it conflates cyclical pressure with secular decline. Moutai\'s pricing power held through COVID, through the 2022 proper